56
00:04:32.870 --> 00:04:40.420
John Hasse: Oh, it speaks to me on many levels. Emotional… The values it expresses…

57
00:04:40.970 --> 00:04:45.370
John Hasse: In turn, in jazz, it's the rhythm and syncopation and the fact that

58
00:04:45.650 --> 00:04:48.939
John Hasse: Every jazz performance is supposed to be different.

59
00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:55.629
John Hasse: the previous performance, fresh because of improvisation. And I like the challenge of playing jazz, because

60
00:04:55.990 --> 00:04:59.620
John Hasse: You always have to keep it fresh. You can never play the same thing twice.

61
00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:03.360
John Hasse: And, every day of my life, I've listened to classical music.

62
00:05:03.510 --> 00:05:04.870
John Hasse: I deeply love that.

63
00:05:05.110 --> 00:05:07.930
John Hasse: But I, I, I have,

64
00:05:08.520 --> 00:05:10.939
John Hasse: special admiration for jazz because of…

65
00:05:11.180 --> 00:05:14.690
John Hasse: A really good jazz musician has to be able to do everything

66
00:05:14.820 --> 00:05:20.329
John Hasse: A really good classical music institution does, but also compose at the speed of thought.

67
00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:24.940
John Hasse: To improvise, and that takes… Great, great skill.

68
00:05:26.060 --> 00:05:32.560
Julie Stout: Do you think that came to you naturally, or did you… when you did that training with the two people in New York, I think you said?

69
00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:39.630
Julie Stout: Did they, like, help you along to learn how to do that and improvise and everything, or what would you say?

70
00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:53.120
John Hasse: Yes, my mother said that Before I could… walk, I'd stand in the… Crib, holding onto the railing.

71
00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:56.389
John Hasse: And sway back and forth to music on the radio.

72
00:05:57.410 --> 00:06:02.590
John Hasse: And, so I think I had music in me from… from birth.

73
00:06:03.110 --> 00:06:07.010
John Hasse: Both my parents had studied music when they were youngsters,

74
00:06:07.440 --> 00:06:12.450
John Hasse: My father studied violin. He said the dog used to howl along when he played.

75
00:06:13.030 --> 00:06:19.720
John Hasse: And, my mother also studied a stringed instrument, so… There was some… Music in our backgrounds.

76
00:06:21.520 --> 00:06:24.979
Julie Stout: Did your siblings do it, too? Did you ever play with your siblings?

77
00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:28.230
John Hasse: No, but I'd fall asleep…

78
00:06:28.510 --> 00:06:31.790
John Hasse: There's a 10 years gap between me and the next oldest.

79
00:06:31.960 --> 00:06:36.479
John Hasse: And so, I would fall asleep listening to my older sisters play Mozart.

80
00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:41.329
John Hasse: And… Let's see, by the time I was in…

81
00:06:42.370 --> 00:06:47.860
John Hasse: grade school, they had all moved on and were either in college or they'd gotten married by then.

82
00:06:48.200 --> 00:06:55.619
John Hasse: So we didn't… we didn't play together, but they… I'm sure they encouraged me. And my younger sister, who's very talented.

83
00:06:55.980 --> 00:06:58.920
John Hasse: artistically,

84
00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:04.480
John Hasse: doesn't have a very musical ear, I don't think she could carry a tune in a bucket, but…

85
00:07:04.610 --> 00:07:08.340
John Hasse: I don't hold that against her, because she's a wonderful wordsmith.

86
00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:10.679
John Hasse: published, I think, 8 books of poetry.

87
00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:19.590
Julie Stout: So you definitely have, like, creative arts that have run through your family that you think influence you to who you are today?

88
00:07:19.820 --> 00:07:27.060
John Hasse: Oh, yes, my oldest sister, now deceased, Trudy, was a very fine… Painter.

89
00:07:27.610 --> 00:07:35.720
John Hasse: And… My sister, Ellen, who is still with us, He's 10 years older.

90
00:07:35.890 --> 00:07:44.550
John Hasse: Majored in… drama, radio, and television at the University of South Dakota, and she was in plays, even

91
00:07:44.710 --> 00:07:47.530
John Hasse: When she was in high school, and I was influenced by her.

92
00:07:47.780 --> 00:07:50.280
John Hasse: Dramatic in public speaking skills.

93
00:07:50.780 --> 00:07:56.379
John Hasse: And my sister Ann, who… We lost last October.

94
00:07:56.950 --> 00:07:58.860
John Hasse: lived… Her life.

95
00:07:59.010 --> 00:08:01.399
John Hasse: as an artist. She was artistic.

96
00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:07.259
John Hasse: Just about every way, and so… My mother was a, very fine amateur poet.

97
00:08:07.640 --> 00:08:11.720
John Hasse: Published in a number of different, literary magazines.

98
00:08:12.130 --> 00:08:17.400
John Hasse: And, so I'm sure that the… I was influenced by the…

99
00:08:17.620 --> 00:08:19.589
John Hasse: Amount of arts in my upbringing.

100
00:08:21.390 --> 00:08:31.570
Julie Stout: I think it's really inspiring, too, the fact that not everyone did music per se, but they still found a way to, like, express themselves in some way as well, which is really awesome.

