John Hasse: But when I graduated, there didn't seem to be a job

199
00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:56.240
John Hasse: For me, with my particular specialty, I wanted to teach the history of American music and jazz and…

200
00:16:57.450 --> 00:17:01.779
John Hasse: Couldn't find a job, so… I enrolled, I applied to…

201
00:17:02.760 --> 00:17:08.259
John Hasse: mini MBA programs at NYU and Wharton, and got into both. I went to Wharton.

202
00:17:08.609 --> 00:17:14.619
John Hasse: I think there was an 8- or 10-week program. We get daily courses, and… Statistics, micro…

203
00:17:14.960 --> 00:17:21.460
John Hasse: Economics, macroeconomics, finance, administration, marketing, And career development, and then…

204
00:17:22.040 --> 00:17:27.290
John Hasse: corporations came to recruit the 30 of us, and I landed a job at my first choice, Procter & Gamble.

205
00:17:27.550 --> 00:17:30.379
John Hasse: Doing marketing management on head and shoulders shampoo.

206
00:17:30.930 --> 00:17:32.599
John Hasse: Learned a hell of a lot.

207
00:17:33.100 --> 00:17:35.279
John Hasse: But I felt like a…

208
00:17:35.870 --> 00:17:42.779
John Hasse: proverbial square peg in a round hole. I really didn't fit, and it kind of… the job quashed my creativity.

209
00:17:43.070 --> 00:17:48.810
John Hasse: So… I was fired after 13 months, and…

210
00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:59.959
John Hasse: struggled for a while to find a place. Then this job opened up at the Smithsonian, and I looked at it. It said, Curator, Division of Musical Instruments.

211
00:18:01.570 --> 00:18:05.370
John Hasse: Specialist in 19th and 20th century vernacular American musics.

212
00:18:05.670 --> 00:18:06.939
John Hasse: I kept looking at it.

213
00:18:07.510 --> 00:18:10.549
John Hasse: And finally, just before the deadline, I called the head of the search committee.

214
00:18:11.010 --> 00:18:14.139
John Hasse: I said, you know, I don't… I'm not a musical instrument expert.

215
00:18:14.850 --> 00:18:18.610
John Hasse: We talked for a while, she said, you should apply. So I did, and…

216
00:18:19.620 --> 00:18:23.560
John Hasse: I guess there was something like 50 other applicants, and…

217
00:18:25.290 --> 00:18:30.260
John Hasse: after some time, they invited 3 of us to come to Washington for a day of

218
00:18:30.930 --> 00:18:34.020
John Hasse: Talks and, interviews and…

219
00:18:34.160 --> 00:18:35.730
John Hasse: I guess I just fooled him.

220
00:18:37.570 --> 00:18:39.960
John Hasse: Fooled him for 33 years.

221
00:18:41.720 --> 00:18:47.529
John Hasse: So, that was, that was… that became my dream job. I was…

222
00:18:48.110 --> 00:18:50.630
John Hasse: I was like a kid in a candy store, I mean…

223
00:18:50.740 --> 00:18:52.769
John Hasse: It drew on everything I'd done before.

224
00:18:53.010 --> 00:18:56.350
John Hasse: from, field work?

225
00:18:57.080 --> 00:19:11.220
John Hasse: To, marketing, to… writing… For scholarly audiences, writing for popular audiences, collecting… Archiving…

226
00:19:11.960 --> 00:19:15.690
John Hasse: Speaking to the press, Things like that, and…

227
00:19:15.800 --> 00:19:18.060
John Hasse: I did mention, but when I was at IU, I…

228
00:19:19.220 --> 00:19:28.100
John Hasse: undertook a research project on the history of ragtime in Indiana and produced a 2… Record set with a…

229
00:19:28.960 --> 00:19:36.050
John Hasse: Big 28-page booklet, and that one, that won an award.

230
00:19:36.330 --> 00:19:41.679
John Hasse: And I also produced, recorded an album of my own ragtime piano playing.

231
00:19:42.150 --> 00:19:48.339
John Hasse: So, I'd had experience… producing records, and that was useful at the Smithsonian as well.

232
00:19:50.770 --> 00:20:05.220
Julie Stout: Do you think that you're, you mentioned you got to do marketing at the Smithsonian. Is that what led you trying to go to, like, the business school for a little bit, to see what else you could do, or what led you down to, like, for your MBA, that route?

233
00:20:08.160 --> 00:20:09.280
John Hasse: Well,

234
00:20:13.790 --> 00:20:18.330
John Hasse: I didn't want to be unemployed or one of those so-called gypsy scholars where you teach.

235
00:20:18.990 --> 00:20:22.749
John Hasse: One course at one college, and another course at another college, and you're…

236
00:20:23.320 --> 00:20:29.539
John Hasse: Driving between campuses all the time, and… Terrible pay, and no… no security,

237
00:20:30.430 --> 00:20:35.159
John Hasse: So I… I'd done things that you could call marketing ever since I was a little kid.

238
00:20:35.270 --> 00:20:39.640
John Hasse: Gone door-to-door, selling… subscriptions to TV Guide, I…

239
00:20:39.830 --> 00:20:41.569
John Hasse: Popped peanuts and popcorn in the…

240
00:20:42.020 --> 00:20:48.909
John Hasse: university basketball games. I'd started a little… Stamp collector's Club item.

241
00:20:51.360 --> 00:20:56.500
John Hasse: Help market the… the jazz trio and the rock band that I was in, and…

242
00:20:56.760 --> 00:21:03.310
John Hasse: Then, when I worked on this presidential campaign, that was… Until the candidate

