00:22:53.070 --> 00:22:56.090
John Hasse: Survey of Jazz History class, and…

271
00:22:56.970 --> 00:23:00.510
John Hasse: You know, they… without saying it, the university wanted

272
00:23:01.370 --> 00:23:04.419
John Hasse: Them to pass, not fail this class, because

273
00:23:04.590 --> 00:23:09.500
John Hasse: The athletic department would have really gotten upset if their Students had flunked.

274
00:23:10.080 --> 00:23:14.070
John Hasse: So, it was a… It was a really,

275
00:23:14.680 --> 00:23:16.280
John Hasse: Wasn't a good job, and it was…

276
00:23:16.420 --> 00:23:18.870
John Hasse: The pay was $14,000 a year.

277
00:23:20.500 --> 00:23:25.049
John Hasse: And that was less than the cost of housing in LA at that time, so it was…

278
00:23:25.370 --> 00:23:31.660
John Hasse: That was the only… interview I had, and I tried lots of different places, so…

279
00:23:32.020 --> 00:23:36.230
John Hasse: I won't say I was getting desperate, but I was getting, worried.

280
00:23:36.800 --> 00:23:43.140
John Hasse: And so… when this job offer at Procter & Gamble came up, I… I jumped at it.

281
00:23:44.840 --> 00:23:54.250
John Hasse: It was going to be, you know, intellectually challenging, Good salary, good benefits.

282
00:23:54.360 --> 00:23:56.670
John Hasse: Interesting city, Cincinnati.

283
00:23:57.310 --> 00:23:59.620
John Hasse: Has an interesting musical history.

284
00:23:59.940 --> 00:24:03.209
John Hasse: But, it, it, it just… Wasn't right for me.

285
00:24:03.420 --> 00:24:07.969
John Hasse: And although I looked at it at the time as a defeat.

286
00:24:08.450 --> 00:24:12.699
John Hasse: Since then, I've realized that by firing me, they did me a favor.

287
00:24:13.050 --> 00:24:19.490
John Hasse: Because… Rather than getting sucked up into the corporate world, It allowed me, eventually.

288
00:24:19.650 --> 00:24:28.109
John Hasse: to find my way to the Smithsonian as an accidental curator, because I never planned to be a curator, and have this…

289
00:24:28.560 --> 00:24:32.780
John Hasse: Career that was so, they're gratifying.

290
00:24:34.800 --> 00:24:41.390
Julie Stout: What draws you to education? What draws you to teaching, the next generation?

291
00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:47.449
John Hasse: I think teaching is one of the most noble professions.

292
00:24:47.950 --> 00:24:50.070
John Hasse: Passing on knowledge.

293
00:24:50.170 --> 00:24:52.770
John Hasse: You know, and… even…

294
00:24:53.160 --> 00:24:58.289
John Hasse: If you're well up on the ladder, reaching down and pulling the next person up behind you.

295
00:24:58.520 --> 00:25:02.689
John Hasse: Helping people Learn, fulfill their potential, succeed.

296
00:25:04.600 --> 00:25:09.779
John Hasse: after all, children and young people are the future. I mean, that's such a corny thing to say, but…

297
00:25:09.910 --> 00:25:14.090
John Hasse: That weighed a lot on my mind, and…

298
00:25:16.920 --> 00:25:19.460
John Hasse: Just speaks to my core values.

299
00:25:21.800 --> 00:25:37.389
Julie Stout: And leading from that into your creatorship, role at the Smithsonian, can you tell me a little bit more about that? Because I know you mentioned you were able to fit so many different, like, things into it, like marketing, like teaching, like, collecting.

300
00:25:37.390 --> 00:25:39.149
John Hasse: Can you tell me more about that?

301
00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:47.140
John Hasse: Yeah, the… Responsibilities of a Smithsonian curator we're…

302
00:25:50.200 --> 00:25:53.439
John Hasse: Somewhat analogous to a university professor.

303
00:25:54.150 --> 00:25:55.980
John Hasse: Both have to do research.

304
00:25:58.240 --> 00:25:59.870
John Hasse: Both have to do teaching.

305
00:26:00.130 --> 00:26:05.910
John Hasse: at the Smithsonian, We teach mostly through doing public exhibitions.

306
00:26:06.270 --> 00:26:08.400
John Hasse: Rather than… Classrooms.

307
00:26:09.540 --> 00:26:18.579
John Hasse: And… University professors always are expected to do service, university service of some sort.

308
00:26:18.920 --> 00:26:22.980
John Hasse: We were expected to do museum service or public service, or both.

309
00:26:23.660 --> 00:26:28.690
John Hasse: It was one area in which Most university professors aren't.

310
00:26:28.810 --> 00:26:31.830
John Hasse: Obligated to pursue, but we were.

311
00:26:32.090 --> 00:26:33.110
John Hasse: Fundraising.

312
00:26:33.650 --> 00:26:37.979
John Hasse: Because Congress… gave the Smithsonian, or our museum.

313
00:26:38.500 --> 00:26:42.380
John Hasse: the National Museum of American History, enough money to…

314
00:26:44.110 --> 00:26:47.199
John Hasse: Turn on the lights, open the doors, you know.

315
00:26:47.720 --> 00:26:52.220
John Hasse: protect the national collections, but that was about it. Anything we wanted to do beyond that…

316
00:26:52.790 --> 00:26:56.400
John Hasse: Whether it was an exhibition, or a research project, or…

317
00:26:57.310 --> 00:27:00.590
John Hasse: Recording project, or travel to a conference.

318
00:27:01.750 --> 00:27:07.729
John Hasse: We were expected to raise the money That was a… Huge challenge, I…

319
00:27:07.950 --> 00:27:13.280
John Hasse: ended up being quite good at it, but it was not something I really enjoyed. I hadn't gone to…

320
00:27:13.610 --> 00:27:18.410
John Hasse: I hadn't spent all those years in graduate school to… To do fundraising, but,

321
00:27:18.830 --> 00:27:23.250
John Hasse: It was part of the job, and… So I did it.

322
00:27:24.350 --> 00:27:31.169
John Hasse: And, it was the only place I could have done

323
00:27:31.430 --> 00:27:37.250
John Hasse: most of the things I ended up doing, for example, Leading…

324
00:27:37.940 --> 00:27:43.080
John Hasse: the effort to acquire Duke Ellington's vast archives.

325
00:27:43.520 --> 00:27:51.580
John Hasse: He left behind… about… 200,000 pages of documents.

326
00:27:51.980 --> 00:27:57.079
John Hasse: half of that unpublished music that he composed for his band, the Duke Ellington Orchestra.

327
00:27:57.660 --> 00:28:02.729
John Hasse: Probably couldn't have done that at a university.

328
00:28:03.320 --> 00:28:04.979
John Hasse: Because we got,

329
00:28:05.320 --> 00:28:09.819
John Hasse: We managed to get Congress interested, and they gave us an earmark of a half million dollars.

330
00:28:09.940 --> 00:28:12.319
John Hasse: Toward acquiring and cataloging the collection.

331
00:28:12.820 --> 00:28:20.609
John Hasse: first… jazz artifact I acquired was Dizzy Gillespie's Last Trumpet.

332
00:28:21.020 --> 00:28:22.710
John Hasse: He was famous for having a…

333
00:28:22.880 --> 00:28:25.470
John Hasse: A bent trumpet with an upturned bell like this.

334
00:28:25.930 --> 00:28:35.090
John Hasse: And, Probably couldn't have acquired that if I'd been at a university. You know, it took a…

335
00:28:35.270 --> 00:28:38.460
John Hasse: prestigious National Museum to persuade him

336
00:28:38.630 --> 00:28:41.360
John Hasse: To donate it, and he came down, and we had a press event.

337
00:28:41.660 --> 00:28:51.290
John Hasse: with, with 15… radio, TV, and print reporters, it was… The area was… error was… Crackled with electricity.

338
00:28:51.680 --> 00:28:53.890
John Hasse: And then, a few years later.

339
00:28:54.430 --> 00:28:58.090
John Hasse: I led our efforts to acquire Ella Fitzgerald's archives.

340
00:28:58.690 --> 00:29:06.410
John Hasse: I was able to found a national jazz orchestra, the Smithsonian Jazz Masterworks Orchestra. Again, managed to

341
00:29:07.360 --> 00:29:10.620
John Hasse: Well, we've managed to get some congressional funding to start that, and…

342
00:29:10.890 --> 00:29:15.070
John Hasse: I turn first to David Baker of the Indiana University School of Music.

343
00:29:15.260 --> 00:29:17.700
John Hasse: Who by then was a dear friend and mentor.

344
00:29:18.030 --> 00:29:21.580
John Hasse: To become the… First musical director.

345
00:29:22.150 --> 00:29:34.180
John Hasse: and… in… 2000… 2… I managed to start a national Jazz Month.

346
00:29:34.510 --> 00:29:37.869
John Hasse: It's called Jazz Appreciation Month, or JAM for short.

347
00:29:38.430 --> 00:29:43.200
John Hasse: And it's now… This is its 25th year, so it's silver anniversary.

348
00:29:43.620 --> 00:29:49.799
John Hasse: It's celebrated in all 50 states and in dozens of other countries, and again, that would have been very difficult to do

349
00:29:50.950 --> 00:29:52.630
John Hasse: At a university or college.

350
00:29:52.780 --> 00:29:58.140
John Hasse: Because I was able to get support from the National Endowment for the Arts, National Endowment for the Humanities.

351
00:29:58.560 --> 00:30:05.400
John Hasse: The Voice of America, State Department, U.S. Department of Education, NPR…

352
00:30:06.040 --> 00:30:11.399
John Hasse: PBS, the American Library Association, all these organizations came together to form this

353
00:30:12.310 --> 00:30:15.260
John Hasse: Loose-knit coalition of organizations all working

354
00:30:15.430 --> 00:30:20.080
John Hasse: On a common cause, organizations that had never before worked together.

355
00:30:20.540 --> 00:30:24.020
John Hasse: And again, That was possible.

356
00:30:24.460 --> 00:30:26.250
John Hasse: In no small part, because

357
00:30:26.360 --> 00:30:33.040
John Hasse: I was at the Smithsonian, so… I'm… So deeply grateful for her.

358
00:30:33.750 --> 00:30:39.950
John Hasse: Having been there, and having… The opportunity to do these things and to learn so much.

359
00:30:43.340 --> 00:30:53.599
Julie Stout: The, the idea that you were able to bring your visions to light and pursue these things that you cared about while also spreading, like, the word, and…

360
00:30:53.700 --> 00:31:01.769
Julie Stout: Educating people that this is, like, something that even exists must have been, like, a gratifying thing, would you say?

361
00:31:03.280 --> 00:31:04.540
John Hasse: Very much.

362
00:31:04.540 --> 00:31:05.300
Julie Stout: Yeah.

363
00:31:05.480 --> 00:31:12.019
John Hasse: You know, there were so many… gratifying experiences, and… Yeah.

364
00:31:12.340 --> 00:31:19.939
John Hasse: moments that, I can't come… I can't come up with a strong enough, encompassing word to…

365
00:31:20.090 --> 00:31:21.049
John Hasse: I mean…

366
00:31:21.770 --> 00:31:27.059
John Hasse: There were many setbacks, and a lot of defeats, you know, worked for years to get a…

367
00:31:27.720 --> 00:31:31.599
John Hasse: Collection of materials of Ellington's close collaborator, Billy Strayhorn.

368
00:31:32.100 --> 00:31:36.099
John Hasse: In the end, after pursuing the family for 20-some years, they…

369
00:31:36.490 --> 00:31:41.419
John Hasse: deposited the collection at the Library of Congress, and so all that work for all those years

370
00:31:41.700 --> 00:31:42.979
John Hasse: Went down the drain.

371
00:31:43.220 --> 00:31:54.750
John Hasse: That's just an example of, of… The defeats, and losses, but… And… Lots of weekends, and…

372
00:31:55.400 --> 00:31:58.879
John Hasse: You know, nights, I even… Early in my tenure there, I…

373
00:31:59.030 --> 00:32:01.409
John Hasse: Pulled some all-nighters at the museum, which…

374
00:32:01.740 --> 00:32:05.499
John Hasse: The older curators were horrified about when they heard about it.

375
00:32:05.710 --> 00:32:12.379
John Hasse: But overall, it was such a, it was such a high.

376
00:32:12.730 --> 00:32:16.340
John Hasse: Emotional high of, of experiences that…

377
00:32:17.940 --> 00:32:21.580
John Hasse: I sometimes have to pinch myself, Am I really here?

378
00:32:22.250 --> 00:32:23.939
John Hasse: Herbie Hancock's house?

379
00:32:24.320 --> 00:32:28.180
John Hasse: looking at his piano, I mean, really here at Quincy Jones' house, talking to him, and I mean…

380
00:32:29.310 --> 00:32:31.320
John Hasse: You know, it was…

381
00:32:32.020 --> 00:32:35.860
John Hasse: Am I really here in the South Lawn at the White House with the Smithsonian Jazz Orchestra?

382
00:32:36.080 --> 00:32:38.689
John Hasse: at the second White House Jazz Festival of Asia.

383
00:32:45.330 --> 00:32:55.149
Julie Stout: I think your face says it all. Like, I can… I can see it all over your face, your impression of it, and the fondness you hold towards it as well.

384
00:32:55.420 --> 00:32:56.370
John Hasse: And deep gratitude.

385
00:32:56.370 --> 00:32:58.689
Julie Stout: Yeah, and deep gratitude, yes.

386
00:32:59.040 --> 00:33:02.819
Julie Stout: Do you have… did you have a favorite part of your job? It seems like…

387
00:33:03.240 --> 00:33:10.320
Julie Stout: It… the way you were just talking, it made it sound like maybe seeing these things up close and personal really, like, sucked to you, but of course.

388
00:33:10.670 --> 00:33:12.899
Julie Stout: I leave it to you to say.

389
00:33:14.390 --> 00:33:15.980
John Hasse: Favorite part of the job?

390
00:33:17.730 --> 00:33:18.450
John Hasse: Hmm.

391
00:33:22.570 --> 00:33:24.420
John Hasse: I suppose it was…

392
00:33:29.820 --> 00:33:32.839
John Hasse: I mean, it was fun to reach the people who were already

393
00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:37.090
John Hasse: you know, hip to Ellington and… Coltrane, and…

394
00:33:37.460 --> 00:33:39.350
John Hasse: Miles Davis, people like that, but…

395
00:33:40.680 --> 00:33:48.220
John Hasse: The greatest kick, I think, was… exposing… Members of the public.

396
00:33:48.560 --> 00:33:51.150
John Hasse: To something that they weren't already into.

397
00:33:51.280 --> 00:33:53.860
John Hasse: Didn't know about. Didn't know that they liked.

398
00:33:54.170 --> 00:34:02.440
John Hasse: In other words, bringing more people into… Into the subject.

399
00:34:03.080 --> 00:34:08.409
John Hasse: And, I know this is jumping ahead, but… That's been…

400
00:34:09.429 --> 00:34:11.639
John Hasse: the greatest thrill I've had since…

401
00:34:12.409 --> 00:34:16.610
John Hasse: I started writing for the Wall Street Journal, in 2008.

402
00:34:18.500 --> 00:34:21.630
John Hasse: today, I don't know, 60 or 70 articles.

403
00:34:21.840 --> 00:34:23.000
John Hasse: All in music.

404
00:34:23.429 --> 00:34:31.280
John Hasse: And… It feels like… musical missionary work.

405
00:34:31.900 --> 00:34:35.419
John Hasse: You know, I'm not going door-to-door like some religious sex.

406
00:34:35.850 --> 00:34:39.790
John Hasse: Do… trying to convert the unconverted, Follow that.

407
00:34:40.060 --> 00:34:47.520
John Hasse: religion, but… I am… I mean, most of the people who read the Wall Street Journal or not.

408
00:34:48.190 --> 00:34:57.710
John Hasse: Hardcore jazz fans, or… historians of American music, so… if I can… right… In a way that

409
00:34:57.980 --> 00:35:00.880
John Hasse: Grabs them in the first sentence or paragraph.

410
00:35:01.230 --> 00:35:02.960
John Hasse: Keeps them reading till the end.

411
00:35:03.300 --> 00:35:05.200
John Hasse: And maybe they'll go out and…

412
00:35:05.370 --> 00:35:07.899
John Hasse: buy some Ella Fitzgerald recordings, or…

413
00:35:08.180 --> 00:35:12.960
John Hasse: Go check out our concert by… a fine musician.

414
00:35:14.940 --> 00:35:22.009
John Hasse: That's the most… That's the most appealing thing for me, is to… enlarge the audience.

415
00:35:22.230 --> 00:35:23.200
John Hasse: of curious…

416
00:35:26.440 --> 00:35:44.419
Julie Stout: letting people know how great something is. Like, because you grew up with such a strong, like, music influences around you that it's natural that you want to be like, hey everyone, this is something that I find is really amazing, and I think you would enjoy it too. Here's more about it, basically. Yeah.

417
00:35:44.680 --> 00:35:49.150
John Hasse: Yeah, and, you know, I'm so… every time the Wall Street Journal publishes me, I'm so…

418
00:35:49.150 --> 00:35:49.640
Julie Stout: Yeah.

419
00:35:49.640 --> 00:35:58.960
John Hasse: Because… I never expected To be writing for such a… prestigious publication.

420
00:35:59.110 --> 00:36:01.750
John Hasse: I have no training as a journalist, none at all.

421
00:36:02.150 --> 00:36:09.430
John Hasse: And I… I never considered myself, I still don't, as… A really good writer.

422
00:36:10.380 --> 00:36:15.540
John Hasse: Rather, as a writer, Who values clarity, and…

423
00:36:20.820 --> 00:36:23.549
John Hasse: Writes enthusiastically about.

424
00:36:25.090 --> 00:36:26.839
John Hasse: things that… that I care about.

425
00:36:27.220 --> 00:36:30.489
John Hasse: So I'm… It's something else that I'm bringing.

426
00:36:30.640 --> 00:36:33.640
John Hasse: Grateful for, you know? Never expected it.

427
00:36:35.470 --> 00:36:46.539
Julie Stout: Hey, as someone who doesn't know much about jazz, you're getting me excited about it in this interview, so that's something. Because your enthusiasm does show, it does show through.

428
00:36:46.930 --> 00:36:57.239
Julie Stout: Can you remind me when you officially retired from the Smithsonian, and let me know what that was like for you, what your feelings were on that, and then I'd like to ask what you did after that.

429
00:36:59.430 --> 00:37:04.470
John Hasse: June 30th, 2000, and… 16.

430
00:37:05.410 --> 00:37:13.140
John Hasse: The… Museum put on a… retirement ceremony.

431
00:37:13.420 --> 00:37:18.730
John Hasse: for me, and I was deeply honored that the… head of the Smithsonian.

432
00:37:19.660 --> 00:37:22.439
John Hasse: He's called the Secretary. David Skorton.

433
00:37:22.960 --> 00:37:26.500
John Hasse: Came and spoke, and so did Congressman…

434
00:37:26.760 --> 00:37:28.949
John Hasse: John Conyers of Detroit, who was…

435
00:37:29.310 --> 00:37:33.150
John Hasse: the leading advocate for jazz in all of Congress.

436
00:37:35.040 --> 00:37:40.100
John Hasse: And I said I wasn't retiring, I'm rewiring. I was going into rewirement.

437
00:37:40.690 --> 00:37:47.380
John Hasse: Because, I couldn't imagine just sitting around loafing in a hammock, or… Something like that, I…

438
00:37:47.520 --> 00:37:49.179
John Hasse: Too many things I wanted to do.

439
00:37:50.520 --> 00:37:57.390
John Hasse: It was really… it was a very tough decision, Julie, because I cared so deeply about…

440
00:37:58.350 --> 00:38:00.610
John Hasse: what I was doing, and had so many

441
00:38:05.700 --> 00:38:09.209
John Hasse: acquisitions I had… I've wanted to pursue.

442
00:38:09.580 --> 00:38:12.400
John Hasse: And, you know, I'd spent years…

443
00:38:12.670 --> 00:38:15.700
John Hasse: Building relationships with musicians and their families.

444
00:38:16.070 --> 00:38:23.170
John Hasse: And this is… is such a, Cliche, but it's… Largely true that People don't give.

445
00:38:23.830 --> 00:38:27.189
John Hasse: Money or other valuables to institutions.

446
00:38:27.800 --> 00:38:29.340
John Hasse: They give it to other people.

447
00:38:30.050 --> 00:38:31.710
John Hasse: So, what that means is you…

448
00:38:32.730 --> 00:38:35.990
John Hasse: To build a relationship with somebody before you ask for

449
00:38:36.370 --> 00:38:41.989
John Hasse: They're prized possessions, just like you wouldn't… a man wouldn't ask a woman to marry her on the first date.

450
00:38:42.270 --> 00:38:47.910
John Hasse: You don't ask somebody to give you something that They hold near and dear.

451
00:38:48.520 --> 00:38:51.830
John Hasse: on the first meeting, you… so it… It takes…

452
00:38:53.170 --> 00:39:00.070
John Hasse: Sometimes it takes years and years and years to build these relationships, and… When you leave,

453
00:39:01.290 --> 00:39:04.220
John Hasse: You have to leave most of these relationships behind.

454
00:39:04.620 --> 00:39:07.559
John Hasse: And you don't know who's gonna come in

455
00:39:08.220 --> 00:39:12.369
John Hasse: Who, if anyone, is going to be hired to continue the work that you did.

456
00:39:12.950 --> 00:39:27.929
John Hasse: And the museum… Essentially loses the… The institutional knowledge of that Employee, The connections and the experiences.

457
00:39:30.490 --> 00:39:34.259
John Hasse: It might be even more… of a loss.

458
00:39:36.630 --> 00:39:39.700
John Hasse: Than it when a typical college

459
00:39:39.990 --> 00:39:45.820
John Hasse: professor retires. It might be… might not be, but, you know, if… That the curator has.

460
00:39:47.810 --> 00:39:50.920
John Hasse: Made all sorts of connections, and has… and if…

461
00:39:51.190 --> 00:39:55.389
John Hasse: If she or he had another 5 or 10 years, could have brought a lot more…

462
00:39:56.230 --> 00:39:58.660
John Hasse: Important and valuable material to the museum.

463
00:39:58.890 --> 00:40:10.839
John Hasse: then… It's a loss for the museum, too, so it was… I think after… Almost 10 years, I'm still…

464
00:40:11.150 --> 00:40:16.049
John Hasse: wrestling with that. It's… it's, I don't regret stepping down. I stepped down…

465
00:40:16.170 --> 00:40:17.999
John Hasse: To spend more time with,

466
00:40:18.160 --> 00:40:20.119
John Hasse: The woman I was just about to marry.

467
00:40:20.250 --> 00:40:22.169
John Hasse: I'd been waiting all my life to find…

468
00:40:22.940 --> 00:40:28.570
John Hasse: an amazing woman to marry, and I found her, and we got married in 2016, and…

469
00:40:29.620 --> 00:40:31.630
John Hasse: It's been the greatest thing in my life.

470
00:40:34.650 --> 00:40:42.579
Julie Stout: What is, your impression of the institution today? Do you still have contact with them? Because I know you said you're still kind of wrestling with

471
00:40:43.770 --> 00:40:47.870
Julie Stout: You leaving, but you still wanted work… wanted to do some work?

472
00:40:48.030 --> 00:40:49.870
Julie Stout: How are you dealing with that?

473
00:40:50.630 --> 00:40:52.760
John Hasse: With the Smithsonian.

474
00:40:52.960 --> 00:40:53.970
Julie Stout: Yes, yes.

475
00:40:55.720 --> 00:41:02.300
John Hasse: Will they… as I went into rewirement.

476
00:41:03.040 --> 00:41:06.050
John Hasse: they named me Curator Emeritus, which is a…

477
00:41:06.160 --> 00:41:08.310
John Hasse: They consider a lifetime honor that

478
00:41:08.430 --> 00:41:10.560
John Hasse: cannot be taken away, so I was…

479
00:41:11.070 --> 00:41:15.690
John Hasse: I was very gratified when that happened, and… I still have,

480
00:41:16.490 --> 00:41:22.899
John Hasse: some ties, I have an email, I've got a… A phone number, I've got an ID.

481
00:41:23.560 --> 00:41:25.010
John Hasse: a staff ID?

482
00:41:26.220 --> 00:41:29.000
John Hasse: And when I can, I help.

483
00:41:30.260 --> 00:41:36.749
John Hasse: One or another curator with… You know, connecting with somebody who might be a donor.

484
00:41:37.330 --> 00:41:44.939
John Hasse: I still feel very… loyal to the museum, and sometimes I'll say.

485
00:41:45.520 --> 00:41:48.449
John Hasse: We, when I probably should say they.

486
00:41:49.700 --> 00:41:53.699
John Hasse: But, it'll be part of, part of me.

487
00:41:53.820 --> 00:41:55.879
John Hasse: to my last breath, I know.

488
00:41:57.510 --> 00:42:01.670
John Hasse: It's, it's, it's a… It's a institution I…

489
00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:06.410
John Hasse: deeply, deeply admire and revere. It's one of the…

490
00:42:06.690 --> 00:42:12.499
John Hasse: Smithsonian is one of the world's great institutions, not that it's perfect, It's far from perfect.

491
00:42:12.780 --> 00:42:20.490
John Hasse: It has its challenges and shortcomings, just as any other institution does, but… Its mission is so… Noble.

492
00:42:20.670 --> 00:42:29.770
John Hasse: Its reach is global, its collections are staggering in number, and Variety and importance, and, as…

493
00:42:30.890 --> 00:42:34.709
John Hasse: The director of the museum said, you know, not all the treasures are

494
00:42:35.230 --> 00:42:38.920
John Hasse: in storage or on display, they're… walking around, I mean.

495
00:42:39.590 --> 00:42:41.850
John Hasse: The curators there, so many of the curators have this.

496
00:42:42.360 --> 00:42:45.350
John Hasse: Incredible amount of knowledge that

497
00:42:46.130 --> 00:42:55.570
John Hasse: Including unique knowledge, unique to their research and their collections and things, and… So… It's an amazing,

498
00:42:55.800 --> 00:42:57.789
John Hasse: It's an amazing group of,

499
00:43:03.370 --> 00:43:11.610
Julie Stout: I… all I will say is that I echo your sentiments with what you just said, because this is your time.

500
00:43:11.960 --> 00:43:13.519
Julie Stout: But,

501
00:43:13.880 --> 00:43:19.650
Julie Stout: Do you have any anecdotes you'd like to share of your time there, yeah, that you'd like to share?

502
00:43:20.260 --> 00:43:20.890
John Hasse: Whoa.

503
00:43:21.250 --> 00:43:25.639
Julie Stout: Take your pick, I know it's a bit of a broad question.

504
00:43:25.900 --> 00:43:34.530
John Hasse: Well… Desi Gillespie, agreed to… Back up.

505
00:43:35.610 --> 00:43:39.930
John Hasse: I wanted to acquire Dizzy Gillespie's trumpet as…

506
00:43:40.210 --> 00:43:43.520
John Hasse: the first jazz artifact that I was… to bring in.

507
00:43:43.970 --> 00:43:48.920
John Hasse: And a colleague said, I wrote him a letter.

508
00:43:50.110 --> 00:43:53.360
John Hasse: Days, weeks went by, months went by, no reply.

509
00:43:53.700 --> 00:43:58.220
John Hasse: So a colleague said, Get Lorraine involved. Lorraine was his wife.

510
00:43:58.450 --> 00:44:01.350
John Hasse: So I wrote essentially the same letter to her, and figured.

511
00:44:02.420 --> 00:44:04.859
John Hasse: If Dizzy didn't respond, she probably wouldn't either.

512
00:44:05.330 --> 00:44:07.379
John Hasse: Four days after I sent the letter.

513
00:44:07.610 --> 00:44:15.769
John Hasse: to them in New Jersey, a great big box arrived, and in it was his last trumpet. I think she wanted it out of the house.

514
00:44:18.420 --> 00:44:25.190
John Hasse: And after a couple months, he came down in person to, you know, present it formally, and

515
00:44:26.770 --> 00:44:33.739
John Hasse: there were… the room, as I mentioned, crackled with electricity, and after an hour of regaling the…

516
00:44:34.290 --> 00:44:38.109
John Hasse: Press and the staff with his wit and humor.

517
00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:45.030
John Hasse: A tall British reporter, as if to summarize the whole press event.

518
00:44:45.720 --> 00:44:49.779
John Hasse: stood up and said, Mr. Gillespie, 500 years from now.

519
00:44:50.270 --> 00:44:52.089
John Hasse: What will that trumpet be saying?

520
00:44:53.140 --> 00:44:55.930
John Hasse: Gillespie looked at him and said, 500 years from now?

521
00:44:56.340 --> 00:44:59.849
John Hasse: That trumpet… Ain't gonna be saying nothin'.

522
00:45:00.230 --> 00:45:02.230
John Hasse: The room exploded with laughter.

523
00:45:02.410 --> 00:45:09.669
John Hasse: Of course, I had to silently disagree, because 500 years from now, it'll still be telling stories through the Smithsonian.

524
00:45:10.310 --> 00:45:14.719
John Hasse: That's… that was one of my favorite anecdotes.

525
00:45:16.910 --> 00:45:21.489
John Hasse: Indelible memories, like standing up, on a stage.

526
00:45:22.420 --> 00:45:30.939
John Hasse: In Giza, Egypt, a few miles outside of Cairo, squinting into the sun, and introducing

527
00:45:32.350 --> 00:45:34.879
John Hasse: The Smithsonian Jazz Masterworks Orchestra.

528
00:45:35.790 --> 00:45:40.539
John Hasse: Conducted by David Baker's Indiana University's David Becker.

529
00:45:40.800 --> 00:45:43.090
John Hasse: to the audience of Egyptians in front.

530
00:45:43.450 --> 00:45:47.840
John Hasse: Behind me was the… the pyramids, The Sphinx?

531
00:45:48.040 --> 00:45:49.170
John Hasse: Endless sand.

532
00:45:54.290 --> 00:45:57.580
John Hasse: Just experiences like that, and it was… wow.

533
00:45:58.930 --> 00:46:01.539
Julie Stout: So you were able to travel a lot, as well.

534
00:46:01.950 --> 00:46:07.760
Julie Stout: Through… through specifically, like, that… the jazz orchestra, or like… Something else.

535
00:46:08.210 --> 00:46:12.699
John Hasse: Well, to go meet with… Potential donors of stuff.

536
00:46:13.080 --> 00:46:18.759
John Hasse: Sometimes to go to conferences, and

537
00:46:20.430 --> 00:46:25.479
John Hasse: And then… but the Smithsonian didn't have A speakers bureau.

538
00:46:26.640 --> 00:46:28.980
John Hasse: And I felt underutilized.

539
00:46:29.360 --> 00:46:30.800
John Hasse: As a public speaker.

540
00:46:31.840 --> 00:46:39.469
John Hasse: So… I, would go out, on my own time.

541
00:46:40.680 --> 00:46:42.770
John Hasse: And give talks.

542
00:46:43.160 --> 00:46:44.550
John Hasse: Sometimes, too.

543
00:46:45.110 --> 00:46:49.240
John Hasse: town halls and libraries and museums about, say, Duke Ellington.

544
00:46:49.610 --> 00:46:56.960
John Hasse: or to trade associations, places like the Cleveland Clinic and State Farm Insurance on…

545
00:46:57.410 --> 00:47:02.499
John Hasse: topic of leadership, I developed a talk called Leadership Lessons from the Jazzmasters.

546
00:47:02.980 --> 00:47:11.159
John Hasse: And, that was… That was… another unexpected thing, I never…

547
00:47:11.270 --> 00:47:18.789
John Hasse: My life thought I'd be talking to the… Nuclear Regulatory Commission, or Cleveland Clinic, huh?

548
00:47:19.390 --> 00:47:25.500
John Hasse: So that was a… That was a… emotionally rewarding.

549
00:47:26.840 --> 00:47:34.279
John Hasse: pursuit that I followed for a number of years, and then… In the 1990s, I managed to get…

550
00:47:34.800 --> 00:47:43.980
John Hasse: myself booked on the Delta Queen steamboat. It was plying the Mississippi River and its tributaries, along with his two sister steamboats, the American Queen.

551
00:47:44.500 --> 00:47:51.119
John Hasse: And the… Let's see… Delta Queen, Mississippi Queen, and the American Queen.

552
00:47:51.480 --> 00:47:56.809
John Hasse: And then I programmed a series of cruises for them on the theme, Music of the Rivers.

553
00:47:57.390 --> 00:48:00.250
John Hasse: And, I recommended.

554
00:48:00.450 --> 00:48:01.970
John Hasse: They hire, and they did.

555
00:48:02.360 --> 00:48:06.689
John Hasse: Leading musicians like, The ragtime pianist Max Morath.

556
00:48:07.180 --> 00:48:12.920
John Hasse: the, baritone… William Warfield, who was…

557
00:48:13.160 --> 00:48:15.170
John Hasse: Concert artist who had also played.

558
00:48:15.450 --> 00:48:19.480
John Hasse: In Porgy and Bess and Showboat on Broadway.

559
00:48:19.730 --> 00:48:25.689
John Hasse: Hatberry Ramblers, the… singer-songwriter John Hartford.

560
00:48:26.190 --> 00:48:27.820
John Hasse: And oh, those words.

561
00:48:28.150 --> 00:48:31.100
John Hasse: We're seeing America at 3 miles per hour.

562
00:48:31.540 --> 00:48:36.530
John Hasse: And, stopping at towns you never visit otherwise, like Paducah, Kentucky.

563
00:48:36.810 --> 00:48:39.729
John Hasse: Or there happens to be a great museum of quilts.

564
00:48:40.160 --> 00:48:43.160
John Hasse: or New Madrid, Missouri, which is a town that

565
00:48:43.310 --> 00:48:47.640
John Hasse: There was a big earthquake there in… early 19th century.

566
00:48:48.440 --> 00:48:52.919
John Hasse: so severe that the Mississippi Reversed course, and it rang.

567
00:48:53.190 --> 00:48:55.339
John Hasse: church bells in Philadelphia.

568
00:48:56.240 --> 00:49:00.090
John Hasse: You go to places that you would never go to, and…

569
00:49:01.410 --> 00:49:06.719
John Hasse: You got to hear and talk with these wonderful musicians of various kinds.

570
00:49:06.920 --> 00:49:14.170
John Hasse: So, that was another… bit of… Traveling that was,

571
00:49:16.580 --> 00:49:18.940
John Hasse: Surprising, I never expected any of that either.

572
00:49:20.300 --> 00:49:30.319
Julie Stout: So you guys go across the… not only the US, but the world as well, and, depending on if you're doing a conference, or more talking, or collecting, correct?

573
00:49:31.720 --> 00:49:37.840
John Hasse: Yeah, and actually the… The international travel was mostly

574
00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:43.569
John Hasse: Because the State Department got ahold of me in 2001,

575
00:49:43.720 --> 00:49:46.010
John Hasse: They wanted to send a speaker to Spain.

576
00:49:46.370 --> 00:49:48.519
John Hasse: to Madrid and Barcelona.

577
00:49:48.840 --> 00:49:52.890
John Hasse: To talk about, Jazz.

578
00:49:53.680 --> 00:49:58.160
John Hasse: I don't know why they picked me, but they did, and so…

579
00:49:58.350 --> 00:50:04.550
John Hasse: I was there for about 4 days. It was… And that… Inaugurated a series of other

580
00:50:05.100 --> 00:50:07.069
John Hasse: Trips that they sent me on,

581
00:50:07.250 --> 00:50:10.010
John Hasse: Basically, the Smithsonian lent me for a few days.

582
00:50:10.140 --> 00:50:12.490
John Hasse: And these were anything but junkets, because

583
00:50:12.590 --> 00:50:16.500
John Hasse: You get there, you're completely jet-lagged, And you gotta…

584
00:50:16.670 --> 00:50:18.339
John Hasse: Hit the ground running one time.

585
00:50:18.960 --> 00:50:21.439
John Hasse: I had to be at a TV station at 6 AM.

586
00:50:21.650 --> 00:50:29.549
John Hasse: This is in Nairobi, and they worked you all day and all evening long, and there really wasn't time to do sightseeing. It was just…

587
00:50:31.880 --> 00:50:40.670
John Hasse: lecture, lecture, lecture, radio interview, press interview. But, hey, I was deeply honored to be representing our country and the Smithsonian, and…

588
00:50:40.940 --> 00:50:48.669
John Hasse: ended up… Talking and… 8 African countries, and maybe… 5 in Europe.

589
00:50:50.560 --> 00:50:54.400
John Hasse: And that was… that was an amazing set of experiences, too, so…

590
00:50:54.520 --> 00:50:58.399
John Hasse: You know, I'm just a guy bursting with gratitude for all this. I really am.

591
00:50:59.730 --> 00:51:11.030
Julie Stout: I think that is an amount of outreach I think a lot of people aspire to do, so I think it's really inspiring that you were actually able to do that and be a spokesperson for something you care so deeply about to begin with.

592
00:51:11.210 --> 00:51:14.339
Julie Stout: So, I think that's amazing, yeah.

593
00:51:16.070 --> 00:51:30.070
Julie Stout: So, taking into account the time after the Smithsonian, what are you up to today? I know you mentioned you're still writing, and you still are doing public speaking, but, if you want to talk more about that or other things.

594
00:51:30.180 --> 00:51:31.310
Julie Stout: I'll leave that to you.

595
00:51:34.410 --> 00:51:38.519
John Hasse: Well, I, I give talks.

596
00:51:39.260 --> 00:51:39.980
John Hasse: Yeah.

597
00:51:40.150 --> 00:51:44.160
John Hasse: During… two years ago, Ellington Centennial Year, I was…

598
00:51:45.480 --> 00:51:48.830
John Hasse: I gave 3 talks at the University of Southern California.

599
00:51:48.960 --> 00:51:51.459
John Hasse: 3 at Indiana University in Bloomington.

600
00:51:51.730 --> 00:51:55.350
